  "answer": "A knowledge graph is a data model that represents information as a network of entities (nodes) connected by relationships (edges). Each node stands for a real-world thing (such as a person, place, or concept), and each edge describes a relationship between two nodes (such as "lives_in", "works_at", or "located_in"). This structure enables flexible, semantic queries that can traverse multiple hops and infer connections. Common components include entity types (classes), attributes (properties), and relationships (predicates). Key benefits are powerful inferences, unified data integration, and improved search/analytics over interconnected data. To get started, explore topics like triplets, RDF, property graphs, SPARQL, and graph databases (e.g., Neo4j, ArangoDB).",
